Hi,

we have set up our Bitbucket Server installation to use a network share on one of our storage servers to store the contents of BITBUCKET_HOME.

The BITBUCKET_HOME env-var on the Bitbucket server looks like follows:

{code}
\\net_share\Repositories\stash_home
{code}

Everything works fine, except when we try to create a fork of one of our repositories, then we get the following error from git that is reported through the Bitbucket UI:


{code}
'C:\Program Files\Git\cmd\git.exe clone --bare --shared \\net_share\Repositories\stash_home\shared\data\repositories\23 \\net_share\Repositories\stash_home\shared\data\repositories\62' exited with code 128 saying: Cloning into bare repository '\\net_share\Repositories\stash_home\shared\data\repositories\62'... fatal: '\net_share\Repositories\stash_home\shared\data\repositories\23' does not appear to be a git repository fatal: Could not read from remote repository. Please make sure you have the correct access rights and the repository exists.
{code}

The interesting part for this bug is that git tries to access the net-share with only one leading backslash ... *\net_share*
I think GIT needs some different formatting of the path to the network share to make it work correctly.

Thanks

h3. Summary
Bitbucket Server currently only supports the {{utf8}} character set on MySQL and MariaDB databases, which only allows Unicode characters in the range U+000000 to U+00FFFF to be represented.  Certain characters outside this range (such as emojis like {{🙌}} - [column Symbola|http://apps.timwhitlock.info/unicode/inspect/hex/1F64C]) fail with database errors in various contexts, such as being added to Pull Request comments.

Database migration from a non-MySQL database containing Unicode characters above U+00FFFF into MySQL also fails with errors. 

!migration.png|thumbnail! 

The {{utfmb4}} character set available in some versions of MySQL can represent Unicode characters above U+00FFFF, but this character set is not currently supported by Bitbucket Server.

h3. Workarounds
1. Remove the affected value by query to the instances current database. Since the error is show the affected character which is {{\xF0\x9F\x99\x8C}} in migration fail, web searched the {{\xF0\x9F\x99\x8C}} and paste the image in the SQL query which appears as {{	🙌}}.
(!) Stop the instance and perform the following query.
{code:title=SQL Query to get the id value}
SELECT id FROM sta_comment WHERE comment_text LIKE '	🙌';
{code}

{code:title=SQL Query to delete primary key value}
DELETE FROM sta_comment WHERE id = <id_value>;
{code}

Restart the instance and migrate to the new database.

2. Migrate to another database type (e.g., PostgreSQL) instead of MySQL.

